{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17630375","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17630375"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:15:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:15:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17312"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17312","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17312"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10002"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78698"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10002","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10002"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17312"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64041"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"5725"},{"type":"tags","id":"10735"},{"type":"tags","id":"10736"},{"type":"tags","id":"10737"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23435"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23442"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78698","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78698"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA cytogenetics laboratory receives a sample for karyotype analysis. The technician begins the process of arranging the chromosomes according to standard conventions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the correct method for arranging chromosomes in a standard karyotype?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Arranged by gene density from highest to lowest","Arranged by ascending size from smallest to largest","Arranged by centromere position only","Arranged by function and related gene families","Arranged by descending size with consideration of centromere position"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct method involves \u003Cstrong\u003Earranging chromosomes by descending size with consideration of centromere position\u003C/strong\u003E. In a standard karyotype, chromosomes are organized into seven groups (A-G) based primarily on their size and centromere position. Specific banding patterns help identify individual chromosomes within each group.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArranged by gene density from highest to lowest\u003C/strong\u003E - While chromosomes vary in gene density, this is not the basis for karyotype organization\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArranged by ascending size from smallest to largest\u003C/strong\u003E - Convention requires arrangement by descending rather than ascending size\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArranged by centromere position only\u003C/strong\u003E - While centromere position is important, size is the primary organizing principle\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArranged by function and related gene families\u003C/strong\u003E - Related genes can be found across different chromosomes, making this impractical for karyotype organization\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe standard karyotype arrangement allows for consistent chromosome identification and easier detection of numerical and structural abnormalities. Autosomes are numbered 1-22 in descending size order, while sex chromosomes are designated as X and Y and placed at the end.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A normal human karyotype contains 46 chromosomes arranged in 23 pairs.","Chromosomes are arranged by size, centromere position, and banding pattern in a standard karyotype.","Autosomes are numbered 1-22 in descending size order, while sex chromosomes are designated X and Y."],"references":["Turnpenny PD, Ellard S. Emery\u0027s Elements of Medical Genetics E-Book: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2011","Harris, D. T., \u0026 Jones, D. R. Chromosome analysis and karyotyping. In: Genetics in Medicine. 8th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2015. p. 375-398","Gardner, R. J. M., \u0026 Sutherland, G. R. Chromosome analysis: Principles and practice. In: Chromosome Abnormalities and Genetic Counseling. 4th ed. Oxford: Oxford University Press; 2019. p. 12-34"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64041"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17312"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64041","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64041"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T09:55:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T15:56:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10002"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78698"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","s